<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-500-119  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 500 119.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Oct 8 1990 n321 p2(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Feds quit FTS 2000 suit. (Federal Telecommunications System 2000)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Jeffrey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Following an investigation, the US Dept of Justice decides not totake part in a $300 million law suit against US Sprint filed byformer Sprint employees.andP;  The former employees contend that USSprint conspired with a General Services Administration consultantto illegally obtain information on rival bids in the FederalTelecommunications System 2000 contract.andP;  FTS 2000 is a 10-yearcontract for integrated voice and data services valued at $25billion which is jointly held by US Sprint and AT and T. The FBIinitiated an investigation into the charges of the formeremployees in Oct 1989.andP;  The charges centered on allegations thatUS Sprint illegally obtained proposal and pricing informationpertaining to FTS 2000 bids filed by MCI Communications Corp andMartin Marietta Corp. An FBI investigation turned up noinformation to support the charges, the Justice Department says.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   US Sprint Communications Co. (cases)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (cases).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Telecommunications ServicesGovernment ContractsInvestigationsLaw SuitUnited States. Department of JusticeFederal Telecommunications System 2000United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationCompetitive Bidding.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>